# Start of question: what changes with frequency?
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:what changes with frequency?
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
You have two identical strings under the same tension.  Each is connected to an oscillator which sends waves down the string.  The oscillator on string  A is set to a high frequency (say, 20 Hz).  The oscillator on string B is set to a low frequency (say, 2 Hz).  Which statement is most correct?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
The speeds of the waves on both strings are the same.  The waves on string B have a longer wavelength.
:ANSWER2:0:H
The speeds of the waves on both strings are the same.  The waves on string B have a shorter wavelength.
:ANSWER3:0:H
The waves on both strings have the same wavelength.  The waves on string B move at a higher speed.
:ANSWER4:0:H
The waves on both strings have the same wavelength.  The waves on string B move at a lower speed.
:CAT:1-D Waves
:Used By1:2869847504,3059011264,3183398896
:Used By3:3183398896,2869847504
# End of question: what changes with frequency?

# Start of question: pitch from frequency
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:pitch from frequency
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
A speaker produces a sound of some frequency and pressure amplitude.  It then produces a second sound of the same pressure amplitude but higher frequency.  How will the two sounds differ according to your hearing (assuming that you can hear).
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
The second sound will be higher pitched.
:ANSWER2:0:H
The second sound will be lower pitched.
:ANSWER3:0:H
The second sound will be louder (higher volume).
:ANSWER4:0:H
The second sound will be quieter (lower volume).
:ANSWER5:0:H
You will not hear any difference.  The difference between the sounds could only be detected with a sonometer.
:CAT:1-D Waves
:Used By1:2870827076,3068562600,3183398896
:Used By3:3183398896,2870827076
# End of question: pitch from frequency

# Start of question: What travels in a sound wave?
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:What travels in a sound wave?
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
A speaker is playing a steady note.  Sound waves are travelling from the speaker to your ears.  What do we mean by "the sound wave is travelling"?  i.e. what is actually moving from the speaker to your ear?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
condensations (regions of higher pressure and density) and rarefactions (regions of lower pressure and density
:ANSWER2:0:H
crests and troughs just like in a water wave
:ANSWER3:0:H
wiggles of the air move and push molecules along with them
:ANSWER4:0:H
molecules of the air move from the speaker to your ear in bunches that we identify as the wave crests.
:CAT:1-D Waves
:Used By1:2870827076,3068562600,3183398896
:Used By3:3183398896,2870827076
# End of question: What travels in a sound wave?

