:TITLE:speeds of waves of different wavelength on string
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
You are holding one end of a rope.  You give the rope a short, sharp twitch so that a wave propagates down it.  You then give it a slower twitch so that a longer wave propagates down the string.  Which of the two waves travels faster?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
Both travel at the same speed
:ANSWER2:0:H
The wave produced by the short sharp twitch (the shorter wave) travels faster
:ANSWER3:0:H
The wave produced by the slower twitch (the longer wave) travels faster
:ANSWER4:0:H
It depends on the rope
:CAT:1-D Waves
:Used By1:2869847504,3059011264,3183398896
:Used By3:3183398896,2869847504
# End of question: speeds of waves of different wavelength on string

# Start of question: wavelength from frequency
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:wavelength from frequency
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
You are holding the end of a rope.  You move your hand back and forth repeatedly with a period of 1.0 s to produce a train of waves which propagate down the rope.  You now move your hand back and forth repeatedly with a period of 0.5 s to produce a new train of waves.  Which of these waves has the longer wavelength?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
The waves produced by the motion with a period of 1.0 s are longer than those produced with a period of 0.5 s.
:ANSWER2:0:H
The waves produced by the motion with a period of 0.5 s are longer than those produced with a period of 1.0 s.
:ANSWER3:0:H
Both sets of waves have the same wavelength.
:ANSWER4:0:H
It depends on the rope.
:CAT:1-D Waves
:Used By1:2869847504,3059011264,3183398896
:Used By3:3183398896,2869847504
# End of question: wavelength from frequency

